<TEXT>
president ranasinghe premadasa and 
four members of his cabinet met for the first time thursday with 
tamil rebels fighting for an independent nation and discussed ways 
to end the insurgency officials said 
also thursday officials said premadasa will help the top 
sinhalese militant leader go abroad for medical treatment a move 
which may pave the way for peace negotiations with the extremists 
the tamil rebellion and the resulting sinhalese backlash have 
claimed more than 12500 lives since 1983 and unleashed a wave of 
terror bombings and assassinations on this oncepeaceful island 
nation 
officials refused to reveal details of the meeting with the 
tamils which concluded for the day after a few hours 
foreign minister ranjan wijeratne said premadasa had received 
and approved a request from rohana wijeweera leader of the 
underground peoples liberation front to allow him to go abroad 
for medical treatment 
wijeweera 46 is believed to have suffered a heart attack 
recently 
the front is an ultranationalist sinhalese group which has been 
at the forefront of the antigovernment campaign launched in 1987 
to protest peace overtures made to tamil rebels 
the request from wijeweera was made through chris nuttal the 
british broadcasting corp correspondent in colombo 
nuttal said he received two telephone calls from a front member 
on thursday who said the group would be willing to hold talks with 
the government if wijeweera was allowed to receive medical 
treatment in london the request was conveyed to the government he 
said 
a government statement said premadasa had not directly been in 
touch with the front 
the front last month rejected premadasas offer of amnesty and 
seats in parliament if they gave up their campaign of 
assassinations and calling crippling industrial strikes an 
estimated 3500 people have been killed in the campaign the peace 
offer was accepted by tamil rebels and a fivemember team is 
currently holding talks with the government 
tamil insurgents launched a bloody rebellion in 1983 for an 
independent nation in the northern and eastern regions of the 
country where most tamils live 
an attempt by premadasas predecessor junius r jayewardene to 
end the rebellion by granting limited autonomy to the tamils ended 
in failure after the liberation tigers of tamil eelam the largest 
rebel militia rejected the plan after a brief acceptance 
the peace plan signed in july 1987 also sparked a backlash 
among nationalist sinhalese who said it gave too many concessions 
to the tamil minority 
the plan was sponsored by india and indian peacekeeping troops 
were later despatched to sri lanka to enforce an arms surrender by 
the tamils at least 800 indian soldiers have been killed in 
hitandrun attacks by the rebels since then 
the hindu tamils who comprise 18 percent of the countrys 16 
million people say they are discriminated against by the sinhalese 
majority in jobs and education 
sinhalese buddhists make up 75 percent of the population and 
control the government and the military 
</TEXT>
