<TEXT>
hundreds of american diplomatic and 
military families headed thursday to temporary haven on us 
military bases to avoid possible harassment by gen manuel antonio 
noriegas government 
the problem is regimedirected gangs such as the group that 
assaulted opposition presidential candidate guillermo endara and 
his two running mates on wednesday said terry kneebone a 
spokesman for the us embassy 
kneebone said there had been no direct threats against us 
personnel but that in the past the panamanian government has 
publicized the neighborhoods where americans live 
kneebone said he did not know if that was just propaganda but 
the people around wednesday were out of control 
us ambassador arthur davis announced that us diplomatic 
dependents would be moved to bases after the assault on endara and 
his two vice presidential candidates wednesday 
president bush anounced thursday that davis is being recalled 
that us personnel would be reduced and that both military and 
diplomatic dependents would be moved either to safe housing or out 
of the country 
the united states maintains 10 military installations in panama 
which is us military headquarters for latin america about 10000 
us soldiers are stationed in panama and bush said thursday he 
was sending 2000 more to protect the lives of american 
citizens 
kneebone said 105 us citizens work for the embassy and the 
moving order affected 57 spouses and 85 children 
the order does not affect 21300 american civilians not 
connected with the us government many of them retired 
leo leblanc from seattle said his daughters are away at 
college he was planning to put up three families in his three 
spare bedrooms at fort clayton 10 miles from panama city 
ive been in the service or with the service 25 years 
said leblanc a civilian army employee we take care of our own 
the kirberg family was one of the three leblanc was expecting 
they arrived at sunset unloaded their suitcases in a few minutes 
and looked at their new surroundings 
they said theyd had no trouble but theyd rather be safe 
the panamanians have always been friendly said emil 
kirberg who works for leblanc 
his wife judy boyle said she had been surprised by the call 
it was worse last year and we never had a problem she said 
the kirbergs said they put as much as they could into a few 
suitcases and left their dog with friends 
i tried to take things that meant something to me said 
boyle that included some pillows and a small chandelier 
once inside the gate leblanc said his wife had sped out to rent 
some videos 
i hope she gets some good ones he said i dont know how 
long this is going to go on 
the plan under which diplomatic dependents were moving thursday 
was designed for temporary security and embassy spokeswoman 
cynthia farrell said it was not known how bushs decisions would 
affect the immediate situation 
kneebone said everybody lives in a highrise apartment 
building for security reasons people cant see that youve moved 
as they could if you lived in a house 
its not like the joads moving from oklahoma to california 
you just pack a suitcase for four or five days get in your car and 
drive across town 
all was calm wednesday in one of the exclusive highrise 
neighborhoods where many diplomatic families live almost the only 
vehicle moving in the hot afternoon sun was a beer truck making a 
restaurant delivery 
some people with pets were boarding them out kneebone said but 
others planned to return home during the day to feed pets or pick 
up clean underwear 
panamanian employees of the embassy were concerned both about 
harassment and whether they would have jobs if the size of the 
staff was reduced 
we can do with very few americans here and that will probably 
create more work rather than less for the panamanians the 
spokesman said 
he said the military officials were in a more difficult 
situation because they had more dependents to deal with 
a spokesman for the us southern command said there are 10600 
military dependents in panama 972 of whom live off base 
southern command was operating under condition charlie 
meaning us personnel can go into public areas of panama only on 
official business and in civilian clothes 
kneebone said his family was in the united states because the 
current government had sent him a letter ordering him to leave the 
country 
since we dont recognize that government we opened the 
envelope photocopied it resealed it and stamped returned 
unopened on it he said 
he said he sent his family home because he thought the expulsion 
order and his refusal to obey it made him a target 
bush said us companies doing business in panama also should 
withdraw dependents among the larger companies with operations 
here are texaco and colgate 
a person who answered the telephone at the american chamber of 
commerce said the chamber could not express an opinion or give 
information because this is a political matter now 
</TEXT>
