<TEXT>
the last brezhnev man on the politburo bends 
enough under the pressure of reform to stay in power but vladimir 
v shcherbitsky has not budged from his deepest convictions 
he was named ukranian communist party leader 17 years ago to 
crack down on nationalism in the industrial and agricultural 
heartland of the soviet union and he indicates nationalism is 
still one of his primary concerns 
nationalist ideas exist everywhere but we cannot allow people 
who stick to such absurdities to join perestroika he told the 
associated press 
at 71 shcherbitsky is the oldest of the 12 men on the ruling 
politburo and considered one of the most conservative except for 
reformist president mikhail s gorbachev himself he is the only 
one left dating back to the late soviet president leonid i 
brezhnev 
shcherbitsky a ukranian also is the only party leader of a 
republic gorbachev has not replaced since becoming general 
secretary in 1985 reformers complain that shcherbitsky is 
preventing gorbachevs changes from taking root in the ukraine a 
republic with a population of 50 million 
but shcherbitsky made clear in written responses to questions 
submitted by the associated press that he feels the earth moving 
under his feet 
one can see signs of renewal with the naked eye he wrote 
his aides said they could not recall shcherbitsky ever 
responding to a foreign journalists request for an interview the 
ukrainian leader refused however to take any followup questions 
either in writing or in person 
shcherbitsky is blamed by some for covering up the radiation 
damage done by the chernobyl nuclear power plant explosion for 
restraining the local press and for arrests and harassment of 
dissidents whose political activities would be considered routine 
in the other european republics of the soviet union 
he denied the charges 
some groups attempt to use glasnost and the public rostrum for 
alien propaganda national egoism and even antisovietism he 
said 
schcherbitsky concedes the ukraine is suffering from accumulated 
problems such as severe pollution he said he responds to public 
opinion these days and as evidence he pointed to the scrapping of 
several nuclear power projects and a dam 
in recent months shcherbitsky has come under new pressures for 
change gorbachev has begun public criticism of the ukrainian 
leadership and several new reform groups have drawn thousands of 
people to public meetings six of his aides were defeated in their 
bids for additional positions of power in the recent election the 
first in which citizens voted in large numbers against the 
establishment 
i have to admit i have never run such an active and intensive 
election campaign shcherbitsky wrote of his successful bid for a 
seat in the new soviet parliament he got 74 percent of the vote in 
the dnepropetrovsk area his old power base 
the other 26 percent crossed his name off the ballot since there 
was no alternative candidate 
nine years ago shcherbitsky smashed the helsinki watch human 
rights group in the ukraine by arresting everyone who joined today 
those activists are out of prison and some campaigned for his 
defeat in the election some spent a few weeks in jail for their 
efforts 
the grassroots organizations have drawn thousands of people to 
meetings on ecology expanded use of the ukrainian language 
legalization of the ukrainian catholic church and exposing the 
crimes of stalin 
many of them shcherbitsky said dont understand that we need 
time technology and money to make changes 
he opposes the most general reform group the peoples movement 
of the ukraine accusing its leaders of ambition and nationalism 
that leads the way to permissiveness and national antagonism 
contradicting the interests of perestroika 
though none of the major reform groups in the ukraine is openly 
calling for independence that is a growing source of conflict in 
several smaller areas of the soviet union most recently 20 soviet 
georgians died in unrest after troops broke up a proindependence 
demonstration april 9 
ukrainian activist oles shevchenko says shcherbitsky remains in 
power because gorbachev needs him to clamp down on nationalism in 
the second most populous republic and because shcherbitsky voted 
for gorbachev to become the soviet leader in 1985 
shcherbitsky confirmed that i supported the election of 
mikhail sergeevich gorbachev as general secretary 
shcherbitsky said he has no principal disagreements with 
gorbachev despite creative discussions in kremlin meetings 
a lively friendly atmosphere has replaced artificial 
unanimity and that is a clear and eloquent sign of the times he 
wrote 
shcherbitsky sprinkled his comments with references to 
perestroika gorbachevs reform program he insisted the ukraine is 
pressing ahead with farm leasing glasnost and competitive 
elections all keystones of gorbachevs plan 
gorbachev is more blunt in his criticism of the ukrainian 
leaderships performance 
in a march party meeting gorbachev complained that billions of 
rubles poured into agriculture have been wasted a 320 percent 
increase in investment in the ukraine has bought only a 39 percent 
rise in output in two decades he said 
but shcherbitsky denied soviet news reports that gorbachev 
ordered ukrainian party leaders to pay more attention to 
democratization and to work with progressive ukrainian writers 
pressing for reform 
gorbachev never raised this question shcherbitsky said 
he did acknowledge however that the communist party chief 
expressed some critical remarks and offered advice which we are 
considering 
shcherbitsky refused to comment on his reputation as a 
conservative opponent of domestic reforms but emphasized that 
changes must be carefully monitored 
after all perestroika is harmed by sluggishness and stomping 
in one place as well as by impulsive jumps and overreactions he 
wrote 
