<TEXT>
for two months residents of beirut have spent 
much of their lives in bunkers and basements because of fierce 
artillery battles between christians and moslems here is a report 
on 10 hours in the life of one moslem family 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the munaymneh family and their neighbors 
tumbled into the underground shelter in their apartment block when 
a 155mm howitzer shell exploded in the street signaling another 
round of fierce artillery battles in beirut 
this is only the beginning moaned soumayya munaymneh 35 
as she shepherded her two sons amer 12 and samer 14 down the 
stairs on tuesday will it ever stop 
most of the six families have spent most of the last two months 
cooped up in the makeshift 33footby19foot shelter in the 
basement of the sixstory block in the bourj abuhaidar district of 
moslem west beirut 
the fierce artillery rocket and tank battles that have raged 
between army commander gen michel aouns mainly christian forces 
and an alliance of syrian soldiers and moslem druse militiamen have 
reached an intensity unprecedented in lebanons 14yearold civil 
war 
some days as many as 25000 shells and rockets are fired by 
both sides 
mrs munaymneh clutched two bottles of drinking water her 
husband rafik and the boys carried chairs blankets and 
mattresses 
dont forget anything because we wont be able to come up and 
get it mrs munaymneh told the boys 
life for christians and moslems alike has become an endless 
cycle of waiting out the bombardments huddled in stuffy shelters or 
basement parking lots then foraging for food and water or patching 
up their damaged homes and businesses during the lulls nervously 
listening for the first thud of shellfire that heralds another 
barrage 
there were 18 people in the shelter they slipped into the 
routine of life underground while exploding shells and artillery 
guns thundered above them 
the men lighted kerosene lanterns and huddled to talk politics 
the women spread out mattresses in the sleeping corner and food 
supplies in the part of the shelter mrs munaymneh called the 
dining room the area around a small cooker used to fix tea or 
coffee or to heat canned food 
the children played cards but everyone was tense as the 
explosions shook the shelter 
the munaymnehs who are sunni moslems have missed much of the 
recent shelling because like thousands of other beirutis they 
fled the city 
rafik munaymneh a 52yearold shipping agent took his family 
to damascus syria he brought them back to beirut on april 30 one 
day after arab foreign ministers called for a ceasefire in lebanon 
we thought it was over after the arabs announced the 
ceasefire and we came back because the kids school said it was 
resuming classes munaymneh said 
obviously it was the wrong decision he said 
as the shells exploded the children argued about the caliber 
and direction of the rounds 
thats an outgoing tank shell samer said when a 
particularly loud blast thundered above i bet its that tank on 
the corner 
munaymneh grumbled that tanks inviting trouble the 
christians will start shooting at it 
a few minutes later five arillery rounds hit the neighborhood 
one near the entrance to the apartment building 
oh allah have mercy on us one of the 10 women yelled the 
children screamed 
silence silence munaymneh shouted 
were all ok thank god the shell didnt damage the 
shelter he said 
his wife and some of the other women recited verses from the 
koran islams holy book 
the whispered prayers were drowned out by a flurry of news 
flashes on the halfdozen transistor radios all tuned to different 
christian and moslem stations reporting on which districts were 
getting pounded by aouns usmade howitzers 
the radios the families only link to the outside world are 
kept on all the time 
is anyone talking about a new ceasefire one of the women 
asked her voice trembling 
no one bothered to answer her there have been dozens of 
ceasefires in the last two months none lasted very long 
the intensity of the barrage eased around midnight and najwa 
quoraitem ran up to her familys thirdfloor apartment to bring 
down some manakeesh lebanese pizza made with thyme 
you have to eat to survive that is if the shells dont get 
us she murmured as she passed out the manakeesh another woman 
served tea 
the barrage eased near dawn and the children fell asleep the 
men took turns to go upstairs to check their apartments 
the building next door took several direct hits munaymneh 
said when he came back some people were wounded well find out 
exactly what happened later 
at daybreak the families left the shelter to return to their 
apartments 
no one knew when the shelling would resume only that it would 
the munaymnehs packed and headed back to damascus their 
neighbors prepared to spend another night underground 
</TEXT>
