<TEXT>
the government flew western reporters to 
jalalabad for their first visit to the city since a guerrilla siege 
began march 7 here is a report 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the army says it has driven 
guerrillas away from jalalabad ending a nineweek siege and on 
wednesday the shelling had stopped in the 16th century city of 
gardens built by the moguls 
children played in open spaces bright with lilacs 
afghan soldiers advanced up to 25 miles along two fronts in an 
offensive begun sunday against moslem insurgents surrounding the 
city their commanders said 
as you can see jalalabad is alive said lt gen manok 
mangall chairman of the defense council and governor of nangarhar 
province 
leaders of the mujahedeen the holy warriors who have fought 
for more than a decade denied army claims of ending the siege 
retaking the samarkhel garrison and controlling half the road to 
the pakistan border town of torkham 
mohammad nabi mohammadi defense minister of the guerrillas 
exile government told reporters in pakistan its a total lie 
baseless propaganda the siege of jalalabad continues samarkhel 
continues to be in the hands of mujahedeen who also control the 
jalalabadtorkham road 
president najibs government flew 13 western journalists to 
jalalabad to prove it controls the strategic provincial capital 75 
miles east of kabul 
jalalabad once known for magnificent gardens orchards and 
palaces has been under guerrilla siege since march 7 military 
officials said the city 45 miles from pakistan had been pounded 
by 131000 rockets and artillery and mortar shells 
it lies near the khyber pass astride the trade routes to india 
and pakistan dominating the entrances to the laghman and kunar 
valleys the modern city was built in the 16th century by akbar 
grandson of babur who founded the mogul empire of india 
army officials said at least 523 civilians had been killed and 
3000 wounded during the siege they said most of the casualties 
occurred in the first weeks of the first major guerrilla offensive 
since soviet military forces completed their withdrawal from 
afghanistan on feb 15 
doctors at nangarhar hospital said nearly all the casualties 
were caused by rockets or shells 
we dont even have one patient with a bullet injury said 
dr hafizullah director of the 260bed hospital 
commanders of the guerrillas who began fighting after a 
communist coup in april 1978 had predicted at the onset of their 
offensive that jalalabad would fall within days 
they had hoped to set up their interim government in the city as 
a basis for international recognition as an alternative to najibs 
regime in kabul the rebels are based in pakistan and receive much 
of their support from the united states 
reports from both sides have said jalalabad was in ruins with 
nearly all the mudandbrick buildings damaged or destroyed and the 
remaining residents hiding in ditches or basements 
the scene in the dusty rutted streets wednesday suggested 
otherwise 
most buildings had been damaged by shellfire but remained 
standing although shops generally were boarded shut the city had 
electricity running water and working telephones 
farmers worked in fields on the outskirts harvesting their 
wheat and planting rice lilacs and wild flowers were in bloom and 
the city had an abundance of palm trees and small orchards 
children played in the sun and their elders moved about the city 
on bicycles and in horsedrawn carts sharing the road with tanks 
military jeeps and armored personnel carriers 
some neighborhoods were like ghost towns however more than 
64000 people lived in jalalabad when the civil war began but many 
fled to kabul or to refugee camps in pakistan 
no count of how many remain is available but some said they 
will never leave despite hardship and war 
what would we do where would we go asked bhargar singh a 
70yearold doctor living in a sikh temple he said rockets had hit 
it five times killing 24 people and wounding at least 100 
early in the battle for jalalabad the army surrendered key 
garrisons around the city and the guerrillas came within about six 
miles of the airport which was hit by thousands of rockets the 
runway was damaged a cargo building leveled and the windows of the 
control tower knocked out 
if its necessary planes can land but i dont remember when 
the last one landed said lt col jehangi 42 the airport 
commander 
military officials have not said how many soldiers have been 
deployed in and around jalalabad but estimates run as high as 
30000 nearly double that number of guerrillas were believed to 
surround the city at one time 
when soviet troops left afghanistan after nine years of 
involvement in the war there were predictions that afghanistans 
conscript army would collapse 
col gen mohammad delawar army commander for the area said of 
guerrilla claims of quick victory in jalalabad and the long siege 
that followed theres an old afghan proverb when a man digs a 
well he usually falls in 
</TEXT>
