<TEXT>
a us international trade commission study 
helps document the claim by a manufacturers group that steel 
import quotas have harmed the us economy the group says 
the itc said in a report wednesday that steel import restraints 
have reduced american export sales by raising steel prices 
the 96page report by the independent government agency was 
certain to enliven the debate over whether the us should continue 
steel quota agreements with 19 nations and the european community 
the reagan administration negotiated fiveyear 
productbyproduct voluntary restraint agreements or vras in 
1984 with japan south korea brazil south africa and other 
nations to limit the flow of foreign steel into the united states 
president bush has pledged to continue the restraints in some 
form beyond their sept 30 expiration date but with the steel 
industry newly profitable opponents of the curbs believe they can 
make a case for ending the program or at least narrowing its scope 
the itc said in the report that the curbs caused steel prices in 
the united states to rise by as much as 06 percent in 1985 16 
percent in 1986 14 percent in 1987 and 02 percent in 1988 it 
said the weakening of the dollar overseas and other factors also 
contributed significantly to further price hikes 
as a result of the vrainduced price increases the commission 
estimated american exports in steelconsuming industries decreased 
by 258 million in 1985 673 million in 1986 699 million in 1987 
and 95 million in 1988 
it makes no sense to renew a program that causes such harm to 
american competitiveness particularly when the steel industry is 
healthy said jon jenson spokesman for a coalition of more than 
300 manufacturers opposed to the import curbs extension 
applauding the reports conclusions jenson said american 
manufacturers have been hamstrung by higher steel prices 
the report said recent steel price hikes have been distributed 
unevenly among categories of customers 
price increases were not as great for large steel purchasers as 
for small ones apparently because the larger purchasers buy a 
great deal of their steel through longterm contracts with prices 
set in advance the itc said 
the question of whether the restraints have caused steel price 
increases has divided american manufacturers 
last month a coalition of 374 manufacturers led by chrysler 
corp maytag corp and others was formed to lobby for continuing 
the quota agreements on grounds that the curbs have helped make the 
steel industry healthier 
that coalition contends steel price increases have been caused 
by strong worldwide demand and shifting exchange rates 
the itc cautioned the figures reflected an upward bias 
because of the procedures it used that means the effect of the 
import restraints on prices might have been overstated 
the study was conducted at the request of the house ways and 
means subcommittee on trade 
