<TEXT>
retail sales rose by a lackluster 04 percent 
in april the government said thursday in a report cited by 
analysts as evidence that higher interest rates are taking a toll 
on economic growth 
the commerce department said sales climbed to a seasonally 
adjusted 1399 billion last month after remaining flat in march 
and falling 04 percent in february 
the last three months sales were up 5 percent over the same 
period last year barely keeping pace with inflation said 
economist lawrence a hunter of the us chamber of commerce 
todays report is another clear sign that the economy has slowed 
far more than most analysts realize 
economists had expected a much stronger rebound in april 
anticipating a surge of between 1 percent and 2 percent on the 
strength of higher auto sales 
carbuying did increase for the first time since november it 
was up 11 percent following declines of 05 percent and 18 
percent but the gain amounted to only about half of what was 
predicted 
auto sales have been hit particularly hard by the federal 
reserves strategy of pushing up interest rates to fight inflation 
as have housingrelated items such as hardware building supplies 
and furniture 
what the fed was hoping was to cool off consumer spending 
while we still had an expansion led by business investment 
spending and exports and it looks like its going the fed way 
said economist david jones of aubrey g lanston amp co a government 
securities dealer 
bond prices which move up as interest rates move down rose 
slightly in trading after the release of the sales report 
still jones and other analysts said retail spending is not so 
weak as to push the economy into a recession retail spending 
accounts for about onethird of overall economic activity and is 
closely watched as a measure of overall growth 
excluding the automotive category sales rose a sluggish 02 
percent last month after inching up 01 percent in march and 
falling 01 percent in february 
i dont see a recession in these numbers said economist 
rosalind wells of the national retail merchants association i 
think the economy is slowing but only in selected areas 
the bright spots in the report were sales at department stores 
and specialty clothing shops buoyed by a longawaited rebound in 
sales of womens clothing 
purchases at general merchandise and department store were up 
10 percent following a 01 percent gain in march clothing stores 
reported a large 36 percent gain last month compared with a 05 
percent drop a month earlier it was the biggest jump since 
february 1987 
they must be jumping up and down and breaking out champagne 
bottles said economist sandra shaber of the futures group a 
washington consulting firm that industry has been depressed for 
so long 
shaber said womens clothing appears to be recovering from a 
twoyear slump caused by rising import prices and the failure of 
merchandisers to offer styles appropriate for women to wear to work 
sales of durable goods big ticket items expected to last 
three or more years rose only 01 percent in april after falling 
09 percent in march sales of nondurable goods meanwhile rose 
06 percent following a 05 percent rise 
other categories reporting sales increases in april were 
gasoline stations 22 percent and food and grocery stores 07 
percent michael k evans an economic consultant in washington 
said the rise in gasoline sales is attributable to price increases 
categories posting declines included building supply and 
hardware stores 05 percent furniture stores 12 percent bars 
and restaurants 09 percent and drug stores 16 percent 
