<DOCNO> AP890511-0114 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
britains new official secrets act got the royal 
seal of approval thursday even though it has been denounced by 
critics as a government assault on the publics right to know 
prime minister margaret thatchers government called it an 
improvement on the original 1911 act which contained 2000 
different ways of charging someone with revealing official 
information however trivial without authorization 
critics said the new laws major flaw is that it denies 
officials who leak information about improper or questionable 
government conduct the defense that they acted in the public 
interest or that the information has already been published 
elsewhere 
the law received the royal assent a final formality before 
taking effect later this year the home office said no date has 
been announced 
the 1911 law hastily passed during a german spy scare has 
given britain the reputation of being one of the most secretive 
western democracies 
technically it covered everything from the civil services tea 
intake to the fertilizer applied to buckingham palaces flowerbeds 
home secretary douglas hurd said the new legislation removes 
from criminal sanction the unauthorized disclosure of large 
quantities of official information substantial as well as trivial 
including disclosures which might merely embarrass or inconvenience 
the government of the day 
introduced after months of controversy and debate the new law 
codifies the governments right to secrecy in six specified areas 
covering defense the security services crime prevention and 
detection and international relations 
the only automatic offenses will be leaking or publicizing 
security service bugging telephone tapping and mail interception 
in other cases of unauthorized disclosures by journalists or the 
800000 civil servants diplomats and defense industry workers who 
have taken an official secrets act oath prosecutors will have to 
prove a damaging disclosure has been made about a branch of 
government 
the government says that by shifting the burden of proof to the 
prosecution it has enhanced civil liberties it also says the new 
law is an improvement because the receiver of unauthorized 
information is no longer liable to prosecution 
but critics say that by specifically excluding the public 
interest defense the government has set freedom back newspapers 
say the government will have little difficulty finding expert 
witnesses such as retired military officers to testify that 
publication was damaging 
what of the man who breaks down the door of a strangers house 
to save a child from fire asked john birt deputy director of 
the bbc writing in the newspaper the independent there may 
well be damage but what counts are the good consequences of his 
actions 
the new law retains the lifetime gag on members of the mi5 and 
mi6 intelligence agencies and continues to shield the intelligence 
services from any parliamentary scrutiny 
the government has drawn the cloak of secrecy even more 
tightly around the operations of the security and intelligence 
services says article 19 an anticensorship organization 
since coming to power in 1979 mrs thatchers government has 
mounted at least 24 prosecutions under the official secrets act 
compared with 34 in the previous 68 years 
in 1985 a jury acquitted civil servant clive ponting saying he 
acted in the public interest in exposing a government coverup 
surrounding the sinking of an argentine cruiser in the falkland 
islands war under the new law ponting likely would have been 
convicted 
civil libertarians claim freedom of expression has shrunk during 
the thatcher era they cite the governments increasing use of 
court injunctions to suppress news its futile threeyear battle to 
ban spycatcher a retired intelligence agents memoirs a 
police raid on bbc studios to seize tapes an attempt to suppress a 
tv documentary questioning the governments version of the killing 
of three irish terrorist suspects a ban on broadcast interviews 
with irish militants 
at a news conference thursday lord stockton chairman of 
macmillan publishers said he was very frightened that every day 
takes a step closer to tyranny the mechanisms of tyranny seem 
to be inbuilt in our society 
labor lawmaker norman buchan said he was concerned that 
secrecy is now becoming a kind of a habit of governments and as 
soon as you have secrecy in government actions tyranny is an 
almost inevitable consequence 
</TEXT>
