<TEXT>
elderly people suffer less depression and 
anxiety by the time seven months pass after a spouses death than 
do younger people a study suggests 
their reactions may be eased by a feeling that death is expected 
in old people and the experience of having lost friends and 
relatives before suggested researcher sidney zisook of the 
university of california at san diego 
they may also escape a stigma that can affect younger widows and 
widowers who suddenly find themselves single in a peer group of 
couples and perhaps perceived as a sexual rival by others of the 
same gender he said 
zisook presented the study of more than 300 widows and widowers 
wednesday at the annual meeting of the american psychiatric 
association 
he said the sample overrepresented white and middleclass 
people ages ranged from 26 to 85 years with an average of 61 
years seventyone percent were female 
the subjects had been married an average of 32 years and 64 
percent had lost the spouse to an illness lasting more than three 
months 
eightyeight percent of the survivors reported grieving two 
months after the death and those people tended to show more 
depression and anxiety than nongrievers one year after the loss 
zisook said 
that finding does not support the idea that active grieving in 
the short run helps longerterm adjustment he said 
to study agerelated differences zisook and coauthors split 
the group into 94 people of ages 26 to 55 175 people of ages 56 to 
69 and 77 people of ages 70 and older 
the oldest group showed the least amount of depression seven 
months after the loss as measured by three independent standards 
by one yardstick 11 percent of the oldest group had moderate to 
severe depression at seven months in contrast to 29 percent of the 
youngest group and 23 percent of the middle group 
the oldest group also showed less anxiety than the younger 
groups at two months and seven months after the loss 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

