the navy will have 110 fewer f14 fighter 
planes than it says it needs by 1996 according to a study released 
thursday by a congressman seeking to save the grummanbuilt jet 
no matter how you slice the bushcheney budget it comes up 
dangerously short in navy aircraft said rep george 
hochbrueckner dny who requested the study by the congressional 
research service of the library of congress 
the report described in its introduction as a quick rough 
analysis concludes that the navy will have 417 f14 tomcats at 
the end of fiscal 1996 110 fewer than it has said it will need 
the study assumes there will be an increased demand for f14s as 
two aircraft carriers are converted from airwings which carry no 
f14s to airwings which carry 20 each and projects a loss of 70 
f14s during the period due to peacetime accidents 
battle lines were drawn last month when defense secretary dick 
cheney submitted his fiscal 1990 budget to congress which saved 
360 million by cutting orders for 12 new f14ds 
