a senior military official accused 
neighboring pakistan on thursday of planning to invade afghanistan 
capture two major cities and turn them over to moslem guerrillas 
lt gen abdul haq olumy told a news conference the plan was to 
attack the eastern city of jalalabad and kandahar in the south on 
sunday 
the general is secretary of the national defense council and a 
ranking member of the communist party central committee 
president najib who uses only one name has repeatedly accused 
pakistan of armed intervention which the pakistanis deny 
pakistan serves as a base for the guerrillas who began fighting 
after a communist coup in april 1978 and the insurgents get most 
of their support from the united states china and saudi arabia 
olumy said 7000 pakistani soldiers and militiamen disguised as 
guerrillas had been moved to the border or inside afghanistan for 
the new assault on jalalabad and a smaller force was being 
mobilized near quetter to attack kandahar 
jalalabad the nangarhar provincial capital 75 miles east of 
kabul has been under siege since march 7 the insurgents made it 
their first major target after the soviet military withdrawal was 
completed feb 15 and they initially predicted it would fall 
within days 
