<DOCNO> AP890511-0136 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
fifty years ago long before 
satellites space shuttles and planetary probes work began on a 
national research center that would help make all those things 
possible 
nasas ames research center is celebrating its first 
halfcentury beginning with an aerial photograph friday of 2000 
employees arranged into a giant 50 
over the years thousands of top scientists and engineers have 
worked at ames developing sweptwing planes and supersonic flight 
contributing to the mercury gemini and apollo programs and 
tracking pioneers voyages through the solar system 
they have searched for the chemical building blocks of life 
experimented with plants insects and eggs in space studied the 
effects of weightlessness and looked for holes in the atmospheres 
ozone layer 
the two prominent features of ames have been outstanding 
people and the development of major unique national aerospace 
facilities said william f ballhaus jr director of the 500 
millionayear center 
space exploration was hardly a hot topic in 1939 when the 
national advisory committee for aeronautics predecessor of the 
national aeronautics and space administration founded ames 
research center named for naca chairmen joseph p ames 
when tensions mounted before world war ii the governments 
langley field lab in virginia was seen as vulnerable to attack by 
germany and a second facility was proposed 3000 miles away at the 
armys moffett field base 45 miles south of san francisco 
the threat from japan was considered but the site also had 
lowdensity air traffic good flying weather adequate electricity 
and access to the growing western aircraft industry stanford and 
the university of california 
today ames is in the heart of hightech silicon valley and has 
grown into a maze of dozens of laboratories wind tunnels and 
offices 
when i first started working here in 1971 during lunchtime 
id wander around in the various wind tunnels and laboratories and 
ask people what they were doing ballhaus said its 
fascinating like a technical disneyland 
the flight research building was put into operation in august 
1940 by the fall three wind tunnels were under construction to 
work on problems of theoretical aerodynamics 
when the united states entered world war ii the basic research 
naca emphasized was phased out while labs concentrated on immediate 
problems 
research on deicing airplane wings had started at langley as 
early as 1927 but the problem was licked at ames in 1944 proving 
the effectiveness of the new laboratory 
in 1952 harvey allen a specialist in highspeed theoretical 
aerodynamics was working on missile research when he developed the 
bluntbody theory which would later solve the problem of 
heating during a spacecrafts reentry into the atmosphere 
that theory would shape project mercurys reentry capsule and 
play a key role in the design of the gemini and apollo crafts and 
their heat shields 
ames work on highspeed flight helped lead to capt charles 
yeagers first supersonic flight in the bell x1 on october 14 
1947 eight years later ames researcher rt jones came up with the 
supersonic area rule which minimized drag on supersonic craft 
and allowed still faster planes 
in 1958 ames invented the lifting body wingless craft able to 
fly back into the atmosphere from space survive entry heating and 
land that idea eventually led to the space shuttle 
ames was given responsibility for basic research in life 
sciences in 1961 and began studying the chemical evolution of life 
in the 1970s ames broke new scientific ground with its pioneer 
series of space probe pioneer 10 launched in 1972 became the 
first craft to go through the asteroid belt and returned the first 
closeup pictures of jupiter 
four years later the search for extraterrestrial intelligence 
began at ames a program that listens for radio signals from other 
civilizations 
ames has had a big impact on the space program and on other 
sciences and it still is very important said ballhaus the 
work here is helping us understand the universe and our 
environment 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

