<TEXT>
gov neil goldschmidt and legislative leaders 
are asking voters statewide to approve a property tax formula that 
opponents say would take control of school financing out of local 
hands 
supporters say the measure will aid about 100 public school 
districts with inadequate property tax bases some dating to the 
early 1900s a property tax base is an amount a school district can 
levy each year without seeking voter approval 
measure 1 on the ballot tuesday would reset all districts tax 
bases to include whatever extra levies local voters have approved 
to make ends meet in 198889 
under the state constitution the tax base can automatically 
increase by up to 6 percent a year so broadening the base will 
make for bigger automatic increases each year 
supporters say this change is the next step in getting oregon 
out of a crisis that had schools closing for lack of money a few 
years ago 
the first step a safety net law passed in 1987 allowed 
schools in danger of shutting down to fall back on the previous 
years tax levies without additional voter approval however 
school officials trying to make budgets on 2yearold tax levies 
say they dont have enough money to cope with inflation enrollment 
increases and other needs 
goldschmidt a democrat and legislators from both parties argue 
that measure 1 will bring some stability to school financing until 
a new source of funds can be developed 
this is just a step as was the safety net toward equity 
said senate president john kitzhaber there are no losers in 
this only degrees of winners 
only about a third of the states 303 school districts are 
potentially affected by the legislatures ballot proposal they are 
mostly rural and relatively small meaning voters from the large 
urban districts are likely to determine the fate of their tax bases 
it tests whether people view schools as a statewide or local 
responsibility said john danielson lobbyist for the oregon 
education association the states largest teachers union 
clyde brummell of portland a longtime tax critic and president 
of the oregon state homeowners association said the issue is 
whether taxpayers want remote voters to determine their taxes 
the main thing we object to in the property tax is its simply 
no longer fair he said until the system is changed theres 
no need to go through with this mediocre approach 
passage of measure 1 automatically would enact a companion bill 
with 112 million in special school aid and property tax relief it 
includes 35 million for educating handicapped students 35 
million for districts with high property tax rates and 22 million 
to ensure no districts get less basic aid under the legislatures 
actions this year than they now receive 
the bill also provides 20 million with the aim of limiting 
homeowner property tax bills for schools to no more than 5 percent 
of income 
