the ford foundation said thursday the nations 
welfare system needs a 29 billion overhaul to expand the social 
safety net with services like treatment on demand for drug and 
alcohol problems and longterm care for the elderly 
other recommendations include expanding the head start program 
for 3 and 4 year olds assuring all pregnant women access to 
prenatal and wellbaby care raising the minimum wage and requiring 
welfare recipients to work after receiving benefits for a certain 
period of time 
the foundations report the common good social welfare and 
the american future is the result of a threeyear 3 million 
study by a panel of business civic labor and civil rights leaders 
and educators 
the current social welfare system is out of date and severe 
gaps in protection and opportunity for millions of americans 
remain said irving s shapiro panel chairman the current 
system leaves too many people dependent and vulnerable at 
critical stages in their lives he said 
the panel recommends financing the broad array of additional 
welfare education and health care benefits by taxing social 
security benefits that exceed recipients lifetime contributions 
such a tax would raise more than half the 29 billion annual cost 
of the recommended programs 
the federal government now spends 500 billion a year on social 
programs 
the report proposes spending 62 billion in federal support to 
expand programs such as women infants and children head start and 
medicaid all pregnant women would have access to prenatal and 
wellbaby clinics and 900000 more 3 and 4yearolds would 
participate in the head start program 
states and local governments would be encouraged to begin and 
strengthen programs to combat teen pregnancies to reduce the high 
school dropout rate and coordinate training and youth guidance 
programs 
about 1 billion would be spent to provide drug and alcohol 
treatment on demand 
also the estimated 37 million uninsured would be covered by 
health insurance through a blending of employerbased insurance and 
an expansion of medicaid employers who did not offer a basic 
package of health insurance to its workers would be required to 
contribute to a public fund that would finance coverage for those 
not working and uninsured 
the panels plan would permit unemployed people to receive 
lumpsum payments so they can relocate to areas of greater 
employment opportunities and the minimum wage would be raised to 
restore the purchasing power of the 1981 level 
