the soviet union could produce a bumper grain 
crop this year of 210 million metric tons up 8 percent from last 
years production the agriculture department said thursday 
in its first forecast of 1989 soviet grain production the 
department said prospects stem from a relatively good growing 
season to date but moscows push for greater output of livestock 
products for soviet consumers will mean record grain use and 
continued large grain imports to cover shortfalls the report 
said 
the forecast included 915 million tons of wheat 1055 million 
tons of coarse grains such as corn and barley and 13 million tons 
of miscellaneous grains and pulses 
last year when production was 1951 million tons the harvest 
included about 844 million tons of wheat 975 million tons of 
coarse grains and more than 131 million tons of miscellenous 
crops 
if realized the forecast of 210 million tons would mean that 
soviet grain production has exceeded 200 million tons in three of 
the last four years an unprecedented production record by that 
country the alltime high grain output was 2374 million tons in 
1978 
imports of grain by the soviet union in the 198990 trade year 
which will begin on july 1 were forecast at 33 million tons down 
from 385 million tons estimated for the current year but still 
on a par with the average of the past decade the report said 
the push to increase livestock product output has increased 
the demand for imported corn and grains for feed the report 
said in addition another year of strong wheat prices is likely 
to discourage soviet imports of feed wheat total wheat imports 
are projected to decline to 12 million tons the lowest level since 
197980 
department analysts said the good outlook for the soviet grain 
crop and high world prices for wheat are likely to limit moscows 
wheat imports to not much more than the levels required under 
various longterm agreements with supplying countries 
