farmers soon will be harvesting a skimpy 
winter wheat crop estimated at 143 billion bushels the smallest 
in 11 years the agriculture department said thursday 
although farmers boosted plantings this years harvest is 
expected to be down 8 percent from last years 156 billion bushels 
because of lingering drought in kansas and some of the other major 
production areas 
officials said the average yield based on indications as of may 
1 was estimated at 349 bushels per harvested acre compared with 
last years 392 bushels per acre 
farmers are expected to have about 410 million acres for 
harvest this year up 3 percent from 398 million in 1988 said the 
departments agricultural statistics board 
