<TEXT>
a government report issued thursday said that 
despite 69 hospital closings in 1987 most of those facilities were 
small and few communities were affected because other medical care 
was available nearby 
the report by the inspector general at the department of health 
and human services its first on hospital closings paints a less 
alarming picture of the situation than is seen by many on capitol 
hill and in the industry 
they say the health care of many americans particularly those 
in rural areas will be threatened as more hospitals close their 
doors due to financial pressures including proposed cuts in 
medicare reimbursements 
the report however said the hospitals that closed in 1987 
were small and had low occupancy rates when the hospitals closed 
few patients were affected most could get medical care nearby 
according to the inspector general 69 general acute care 
hospitals closed in 27 states in 1987 while 13 new hospitals 
opened that year eight of the 69 that closed in 1987 reopened the 
next year the report said 
the american hospital association by contrast said 79 
community hospitals closed in 1987 and more than 400 have closed 
since 1980 industry experts project that several hundred more will 
close in the next few years unless financial pressures are eased 
the report made no projections and looked only at 1987 
no single factor was responsible for the closings the report 
said but the common elements include declining revenues due to 
fewer admissions cuts in insurance reimbursements and more 
treatment of uninsured patients who cannot pay their bill other 
factors include rising costs resulting from pressures to add new 
medical technology and skilled personnel the report said 
the 1987 closings accounted for 13 percent of all hospitals 
nationally and one half of 1 percent of the general acute care 
inpatient bed supply 
about 54 percent or 37 of the hospitals that closed were in 
rural areas and 46 percent or 32 of them were urban hospitals 
also the hospitals that closed had about the same medicare and 
medicaid utilization rates as other hospitals 
the report said that despite the closings most of the affected 
communities still had adequate emergency and inpatient medical 
services available nearby 
in 19 of the 37 communities where hospitals closed residents 
have to travel less than 10 miles for emergency care and 29 less 
than 20 miles in seven communities the ride is up to 30 miles and 
its 75 miles an hour by ambulance to the nearest emergency 
services for residents in mullen neb but in all those areas 
ground or air ambulance services are available the report said 
all but one of the 32 urban areas where hospitals closed have 
emergency care available within 10 miles the exception is wasco 
calif where residents have to travel 19 miles to delano the 
report said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

