president george bush is poised to announce he 
will negotiate with congress for lifting restrictions on trade with 
the soviet union if the kremlin reforms its emigration policies 
administration sources said thursday 
bush will make his announcement at a speech friday at texas aampm 
university said the sources who spoke only on condition they not 
be identified 
bush is expected to announce he is asking congress to waive a 
1974 law which links trade concessions for communist countries with 
emigration performance the sources said the waiver will be 
granted if the soviets fulfill their promise to codify new 
emigration laws and faithfully implement them the sources said 
his planned announcement follows the first round of talks 
between the administration and moscow conducted this week by 
secretary of state james a baker iii 
baker left moscow with a list of jewish refuseniks who are being 
allowed to emigrate after years of waiting part of a surge of jews 
and other minorities being let out under the liberalized policies 
of mikhail gorbachev 
last month 4557 jews left the highest monthly figure since 
october of 1979 the year emigration reached an annual high of 
51320 as many as 70000 soviets are expected to be allowed out 
this year 
the 1974 law withholds credit guarantees and import duty 
reductions from communist countries which prevent emigration 
only china and hungary have been granted a waiver and been 
accorded most favored nation status which gives them lower 
import duties when they sell goods to the united states 
the soviets have promised that under new laws strict definition 
would be given to eligibility for emigration specifically the new 
laws would limit the number of years that have to elapse before a 
person with knowledge of state secrets is allowed to leave soviet 
authorities have used the provision of their existing law to ban 
some jews from leaving for life 
former democratic rep charles vanik who coauthored the 1974 
law recently called on bush and congress to waive the restriction 
for one year to encourage further improvements in human rights 
under gorbachev 
vaniks plea has been endorsed by several american jewish groups 
who used to be at the forefront of restricting trade with the 
soviets formal approval of the waiver by jewish groups would 
ensure support for such a move in congress 
