<TEXT>
the state supreme court overturning a 
2 million jury verdict ruled thursday that the reprinting of a 
newspaper article was not libelous even though the article was no 
longer true when it was republished 
the 1972 article by syndicated columnist jack anderson which 
reported that the president of a labor union was under federal 
investigation was distributed by a rival union during a 19751976 
battle over which union would represent state workers in cranston 
and newport 
although kenneth t lyons president of the national association 
of government employees was under investigation for alleged mob 
ties when andersons story originally was published the 
investigation ended a few months later with no charges brought 
against lyons 
the jury concluded that council 94 of the american federation of 
state county and municipal employees had libeled lyons and nage by 
reprinting andersons article without showing that lyons since had 
been cleared 
the jury assessed 2 million in compensatory and punitive 
damages against the council and the parent union 
chief justice thomas f fay who wrote the high courts 
unanimous opinion noted that both reprints included the date of 
the original article in type larger than the text print 
aside from the fact that the original article was dated and 
accurate the text referred to richard nixon as president of the 
united states fay wrote the majority of the original column 
was devoted to a discussion of the upcoming 1972 presidential 
election between nixon and mcgovern 
these historical references indicate that the reprints 
referred to prior events and not to matters occurring in 1975 and 
1976 fay wrote 
the fact that the reprints were published during a heated 
laborelection campaign when the important constitutional 
concerns regarding free speech are greatest also weighed in the 
courts finding that they were not libelous fay wrote 
it was the second time the case had been before the state 
supreme court in 1986 after the original jury had rejected lyons 
lawsuit the justices overturned that verdict and ordered a new 
trial 
