<TEXT>
kenya on thursday urged an international 
ban on the trade of ivory in an attempt to curb the illegal 
slaughter of elephants which has halved africas elephant 
population since the early 1970s 
experts say a dramatic increase in elephant poaching has been 
spurred by record world prices for ivory ivory sells for about 91 
a pound and an average tusk weighs 11 pounds 
the policing of the elephants survival is not easy but it 
will be more practical if any ivory trade is banned n katana 
ngala minister of tourism and wildlife said at a news conference 
conservationists believe there are about 750000 elephants left 
on the continent they say poachers are killing about 75000 of the 
mammals a year if the slaughter continues at that rate the 
population could be wiped out by the year 2000 
an aerial survey last year found an estimated 20000 elephants 
in kenya which 15 years ago had an elephant population of 121000 
ngala said the government will conduct another count in june and 
july 
he said kenya submitted its recommendation on a trade ban 
thursday to the lausanne switzerlandbased convention in trade of 
endangered species 
if twothirds of the conventions approximately 100 members vote 
to list elephants on the conventions appendix one at the groups 
next meeting in october international trade in elephant products 
would be banned 
tanzania and somalia kenyas neighbors to the south and east 
respectively have submitted similar proposals to the convention 
said richard leakey kenyas director of wildlife 
however countries such as japan a major ivory consumer are 
likely to oppose the proposal 
zimbabwe one of the few african nations with a growing elephant 
population has annual elephant kills and a thriving legal trade in 
elephant products in the last 12 months it has earned about 
600000 in legal ivory sales 
ngala said that while kenya realizes some african countries 
would suffer from an ivory trade ban such action is crucial if the 
elephant is to survive 
kenya also plans to fence parts of its wildlife parks to better 
protect elephants leakey said 
since the beginning of the year he said as many as 300 
elephants have been killed in kenyas parks 
</TEXT>
