<TEXT>
the cabildo the building where the louisiana 
purchase was signed stands echoing and vacant only the 20foot 
ceilings and other architectural details hinting at more than 200 
years of history 
large chunks of the ceilings and floors are ripped out of one of 
new orleans most famous landmarks where maps and pictures once 
hung stenciled instructions order repair cracks entire wall 
and remove plaster 
but there are no workers to follow those instructions or to 
replace the third story destroyed by a fire may 11 1988 because 
the state hasnt come up with 12 million to get things ready for 
renovation 
firefighters rescued most of the cabildos treasures including 
the death mask of napoleon a temporary roof was installed after 
the fire but without a third floor to hold the building together 
the mortar between the massive gray stones of the front wall lost 
its grip the wall had been leaning since at least 1850 but 
daylight now showed through the corners 
crews installing inchthick rods to tie the front wall to the 
back discovered a new problem asbestos used in renovations years 
ago that prompted the state fire marshal to check not only the 
cabildo but other nearby museum buildings and order 12 million in 
repairs 
insurance covers 4 million in fire damage but not the ordered 
renovations so state museum director james sefcik is looking to 
the state at a time when gov buddy roemer is trying to cut 700 
million from the state budget 
but sefcik is confident he can get the 12 million its not 
new money he said but funds left over from other state museum 
capital projects 
it doesnt add to the burden that the legislature is facing at 
all its money that is there from the past he said he is 
worried though about cuts proposed by roemer who has said all 
agencies not protected by the state constitution must slash their 
budgets by onequarter 
those budget cuts are devastating sefcik said theyll 
effectively destroy the state museum system if they go through the 
way theyve been proposed i dont want to be the guy who has to 
lay off 25 people 
the amount of money involved isnt that big were talking 
about the cultural heritage of this state its got to be worth a 
couple million dollars 
if its not im in the wrong business 
meanwhile sefcik is asking for 2 million in donations to 
refurbish and improve exhibits in the state museum buildings near 
jackson square 
new exhibits in sefciks plans include getting someone to 
develop a video game based on the 1815 battle of new orleans which 
actually occurred after the war of 1812 was officially over the 
visitors will represent the british and have to attack andrew 
jacksons position as it was at the time of the battle they will 
discover what the british were up against and will understand why 
jackson chose that spot and why the british lost 
other planned exhibits include plantations louisianas early 
and colonial history and the cabildo itself he said one of the 
problems we have is that so much history took place in the cabildo 
that is germane to new orleans and to louisiana and to the united 
states that i wish we had twice as much space because it all 
deserves telling 
new orleans was under spanish rule when the casa cabildo or 
town hall was built in the 1790s on the site of a police station 
fire had destroyed the roof and woodwork of the corps de garde in 
1788 and 1794 but its heavy brick walls and floor remained and 
were incorporated into the much larger cabildo 
after 1803 when the louisiana purchase doubled the size of the 
united states the cabildo housed the government of the territory 
of new orleans the louisiana supreme court and municipal police 
station moved in 50 years later 
plessy vs ferguson the case that established the separate 
but equal racial doctrine that stood until 1954 was among the 
many cases heard there 
sefcik figures it will take about 18 months to develop the 
exhibits but the work cant start until the money is in hand he 
hopes to reopen the cabildo in the first half of 1991 
the combination of publicity about the cabildo because of the 
fire and the new exhibits should boost the number of visitors from 
about 150000 a year to about 250000 he said when all of the 
jackson square complex is open he figures the number could be a 
million 
as tragic as the cabildo fire was and i dont ever want to 
go through anything like that again i think in many ways it will 
be looked upon as one of the best things that happened in the 
history of the state museum he said 
it has forced people to take a second look at something they 
took for granted to understand that all of these resources are 
precious are special deserve better care than perhaps they had 
been given 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

