cheerleader and traveling salesman for what he sees as an effort to 
build americas past into its future by his reckoning the 
preservation movement is the most active and effective force in 
rebuilding and reviving american cities in 1989 
urban renewal tore down what was there and tried to replace it 
with something new the movement as walter calls it seeks to 
revive what is there and put it back to use he maintains that 
works better because people prefer to live shop and work in 
neighborhoods and places they know in buildings with a flavor of 
history about them 
rebuilding with the emphasis on creating housing and facilities 
for moderate and lowincome americans is only part of the 
movement 
it sometimes blocks bulldozers and walter boasts of a leading 
role in opposing development of a suburban shopping mall on part of 
the civil war battlefield at manassas va adjacent to the 
national park that already protects the main site of the battle 
congress voted late last year to buy the land involved 
that and such measures as a 1988 law to protect historic 
shipwrecks and scores of traditional projects to guard and 
maintain historic sites fit one image of the preservationists as a 
movement pursuing worthy projects that really dont have much to do 
with everyday life 
but the same people who fought off the manassas mall are taking 
lessons from the people who build and run malls and applying them 
to the rescue and revival of shopping districts many of them 
shuttered for loss of customers to suburban shopping centers and 
discount houses 
the main street project provides advice and in some cases 
support for projects in 30 states from rural downtowns to old but 
reviving business districts in cities like boston and pittsburgh 
part of the advice is that neighborhood merchants change their old 
ways and adopt the techniques of the malls such as opening and 
closing the shops at the same hours and cooperating on advertising 
and promotions 
the national trusts programs provide loans and grants that 
emphasize restoration for more than its own sake with refurbished 
buildings providing housing community centers and commercial 
space they dont add up to a lot of units but as walter notes 
any dent in the problem helps especially in the era of the budget 
crisis 
a sampling of buildings that trust programs have helped preserve 
a hotel in san franciscos chinatown which now provides 
housing and a community center for elderly tenants living on low 
fixed incomes 
an 1874 municipal building in the dorchester section of boston 
to be converted into apartments offices and shops 
a brooklyn convent built in 1889 now to become 11 low and 
moderate income apartments 
a former ymca in newport ri which is to be rebuilt as 
lowincome housing and a shelter for the homeless 
the national trust has a 26 million budget this year a speck 
in federal budget terms just under a fifth of the money comes from 
the government the rest from contributions and the dues of about 
220000 members 
walter 48 has headed the national trust for five years 
lengthy tenure on the resume of a man who has been a boston lawyer 
a florida state official director of the office of government 
ethics under two presidents jimmy carter and ronald reagan and 
head of the national academy of public administration 
hell need all of his insiders skills as he lobbies to undo 
limits on the credits a taxpayer can claim for investing in 
historic rehabilitation or lowincome housing without the tax 
incentive investment in the restoration of historic buildings has 
plunged by about 60 percent 
putting it back would cost about 200 million a year and thats 
not likely to be a popular prospect in the current budget crunch 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
walter r mears vice president and columnist 
for the associated press has reported on washington and national 
politics for more than 25 years 
</TEXT>
