<TEXT>
a preliminary study by the agriculture 
department says the era of irrigation expansion in the united 
states may not be over 
after irrigated farmland peaked at 503 million acres in 1978 
there was a gradual downtrend evidenced by the governments 1982 
farm census and by a 1984 usda survey many experts believed 
irrigation expansion had run its course 
the report by the departments economic research service showed 
that crop irrigation dropped to 49 million acres in 1982 and then 
plummeted to 423 million acres in 1983 as federal acreage programs 
and low prices prompted farmers to make sharp cutbacks 
some recovery was reported in several years following 1983 but 
irrigation still lagged behind the old peak of the late 1970s 
last year when drought parched crops across much of the nation 
irrigation edged up slightly to 459 million acres from 445 
million acres in 1987 
irrigated area in 1989 could be the highest since 1982 
reflecting strong crop prices moderate energy prices and low 
annual acreage setasides reduction programs the report said 
in the east last years drought is expected to stimulate some 
investment in irrigation as a form of insurance 
in the west where most of the nations irrigation is located 
the water supply has improved from a year ago 
the report in the may issue of agricultural outlook magazine 
was written by economists bill quinby and john hostetler 
crop prices and acreage diversion programs have more influence 
on irrigated area than do weather conditions or energy prices 
the report said after expanding about 30 percent per decade 
from 1900 to 1930 irrigation development slow to 4 percent in 
the 1930s a period marked by low crop prices 
when crop prices rose in the 1940s and 1950s irrigation growth 
was encouraged once again 
the expansion of crop irrigation in the mid1970s was a 
substantial deviation from the pattern the report said that 
was due to favorable crop prices and expanding exports which 
helped push irrigation growth to about 23 million acres per year 
slower growth in the early 1980s reflected adjustments to crop 
surpluses and low prices the report said 
hostetler added wednesday in a telephone interview that last 
years severe drought will encourage people to at least think 
about irrigation and that some will invest in new systems or 
expand operations as a result 
he said its too early to conclude whether irrigation is back on 
an expansion track because all the figures arent in yet 
the report said the national figures mask regional trends for 
example the pacific and mountain regions account for more than 
half the us irrigated area in 1987 the two regions had 241 
million acres under irrigation down about 2 million acres from 
1982 but almost 700000 acres more than in 1983 
last year the west had poor soil moisture prior to planting and 
there was reduced streamflow during the crop growing season the 
irrigated area was cut back to 239 million acres in 1982 the 
area was 26 million acres 
in the plains states which straddle the nation between the arid 
west and the humid east irrigation grew to 137 million acres last 
year from 126 million in 1987 but that was well behind the 153 
million acres in 1982 in 1983 however the irrigated area 
plummeted to 115 million acres 
because much of the irrigation water in the southern plains is 
pumped from deep wells that have declining water tables energy 
costs represent a substantial share of production costs the 
report said irrigated area declined in 1974 and 1982 following 
steep rises in natural gas prices 
the east had a record 82 million acres under irrigation last 
year up from 77 million in 1987 and 76 million in 1982 the 
report said 
irrigation has more than quadrupled since 1969 in the corn 
belt and lake states the report said in these regions 
irrigation is supplemental and there is strong evidence that 
weather affects irrigated acreage 
the easts irrigation is also supplemental used when and if 
needed last years drought helped push irrigation to a record 
level the report said 
