the national stock market commission has 
suspended 11 traders three permanently following a probe into a 
multimillion dollar illegal trading scandal news reports said 
the excelsior news service reported late wednesday that the 
suspensions followed an investigation into the october 1987 crash 
excelsior said commission head oscar espinosa villarreal 
disclosed the suspensions late wednesday and quoted him as saying 
that the act was unprecedented 
exclesior and the government news service notimex identified 
those suspended permanently from trading as jose luis villar 
arguero operations manager for bursamex miguel angel hernandez 
campos a promotions director for the casa de bolsa de mexico and 
jose luis moreno rodriguez of the casa de bolsa fimsa 
the other eight primarily directors and highranking officials 
of mexicos trading houses were suspended from stock market 
operations for periods ranging from three to 12 months notimex 
said 
notimex reported that the commission issued official warnings to 
an additional 31 traders and doled out administrative sanctions 
against another 42 notimex did not specify the type of sanctions 
the investigation followed complaints filed by at least 200 
investors against all but one of mexicos 24 registered brokerage 
firms after stockholders lost millions of dollars worth of 
holdings in the 1987 crash 
the alleged violations ranged from insider trading in both 
stocks and foreign currencies to the sale of nonexistent treasury 
certificates and trading in securities without client consent 
following the investigation officials in february arrested 
eduardo legorreta board chairman and one of the founders of 
operadora de bolsa one of mexicos two leading trading firms and 
jaime ceballos cervantes the companys director of investment 
promotions 
also arrested were juan carlos fernandez cuevo and jose 
francisco rodriguez dupont of mexicana de valores e inversiones 
mexicos other major brokerage firm 
at the time of the arrests gustavo diaz president of an 
association formed by the affected investors estimated the 
brokerage firms netted 435 million in profits from the alleged 
illegal trading 
