the bush administration sent legislation to 
congress today calling for a 500 million federal oil cleanup fund 
to be financed by a fee on domestic and imported oil 
officials said the government now has little money earmarked for 
such an emergency 
transportation secretary samuel skinner outlined the 
administrations proposal for a comprehensive oil spill liability 
and compensation law saying that in light of the alaska spill it 
is imperative to move quickly to establish a federal response 
fund 
rep bill tauzin dla chairman of the house subcommittee on 
coast guard and navigation promised that a bill for such a fund 
would be scheduled for a vote by the panel later this month 
skinners proposal prompted some subcommittee members to note 
that congress has debated but failed to enact such a contingency 
fund for the past 15 years 
it took a tragedy like the exxon valdez to cause the entire 
congress to focus on the issue said rep walter jones dokla 
who is the sponsor of a bill already under consideration to 
establish a fund similar to the one proposed by the administration 
skinner said that while the cost of the oil spill in alaskas 
prince william sound on march 24 has yet to be determined it could 
exceed the maximum of 500 million envisoned for the proposed 
cleanup fund 
under the legislation proposed by the administration an oil 
company or shipper would be liable to up to 78 million in cleanup 
damage and recovery costs costs in excess of that would be covered 
by the federal fund which would be collected over the next five 
years from a 13 centabarrel fee on domestic and imported 
petroleum 
when the exxon tanker spilled 11 million gallons of oil in 
alaska the worst spill in us history a federal oil spill 
contingency fund had only 4 million in it skinner told the 
congressmen that had the spill been caused by someone with less 
resources than the exxon corp the government would have been left 
scrambling for money and asking congress for special appropriations 
whatever the price officials said a day earlier they doubt 
exxon can clean the oil from hundreds of miles of rocky alaska 
coastline by next september as the oil company has said it hopes to 
do 
exxon announced wednesday that it plans to sharply increase the 
number of workers assigned to coastal cleanup duties and deploy 
more barges and boats to the effort the decision to increase 
manpower came after bush administration officials said exxons 
earlier summer cleanup plans were inadequate 
but adm paul a yost the us coast guard commandant told a 
senate hearing that despite the increased manpower he considers it 
almost impossible for exxon to clean all the oil from more than 
300 miles of shoreline by the sept 15 target date 
skinner told reporters wednesday that while exxon plans to 
complete the cleanup this summer he considers it a massive 
massive effort and a big challenge that might not be 
possible 
skinner said the bush administration will closely monitor the 
effort and direct exxon back to work next spring if the cleanup 
does not meet expectations 
nevertheless william d stevens president of exxon usa told 
openly skeptical senators the company fully expects to clean up 
the beaches by september after which poor weather would likely 
make efforts impossible 
confronted by figures showing that only 17 miles of the 300 
miles of shoreline have been cleaned so far stevens said work 
started slowly because the company tackled the worst beaches first 
he promised that even if the september deadline is met exxon will 
return in the spring to ensure the work is done 
the company announced plans to increase the number of cleanup 
workers from 3400 to 5000 this summer after being told by skinner 
and presidential chief of staff john sununu at a white house 
meeting monday that earlier cleanup plans were inadequate 
exxon also said it would increase the number of barges and boats 
used in the cleanup bringing the total to 70 vessels 
the coast guards yost however expressed doubt in testimony 
before the senate commerce committee that the cleanup will be 
anything short of a long arduous task he described how his hands 
dripped with oil after he reached underneath the gravel on a beach 
that 200 workers had been cleaning for 10 consecutive days 
increasing the number of cleanup workers will not keep the oil 
from washing back onto the beaches yost told the senators 
