<DOCNO> AP890511-0263 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
developing a network of magneticlevitation 
trains to replace shorthaul aircraft could save the airlines money 
and reduce airport congestion some researchers say 
standing in the way of development of the maglev system is 
money and a lack of enthusiasm 
the market for maglev trains is not well defined said 
larry r johnson an economist and director of the argonne national 
laboratorys center for transportation research who conducted a 
yearlong study with five colleagues there is not a constituency 
that would push the idea 
in a report soon to be made public researchers at the argonne 
laboratory outside chicago say the costs of building a 2000mile 
network of 300 mph magneticlevitation trains would be largely 
offset by multibilliondollar savings from reducing airline delays 
energy costs and airplane acquisition 
a maglev network could open gate slots at major us airports to 
longer domestic and international flights eliminating the need to 
build many new airports the researchers said 
magnetic levitation uses powerful magnets to lift a train above 
a guideway and propel it at high speeds on a cushion of air 
although the technology exists there are no maglev trains 
operating anywhere in the world skeptics suggest that a working 
shortline demonstration model be built first to prove the 
feasibility of maglevs 
another obstacle is the highspeed conventional electric train 
now in use in france and japan and under development in germany 
sudhir kumar a professor of engineering and ground 
transportation at the illinois institute of technology said 
johnson is right about the need to reduce air traffic congestion 
but he said a maglev system would be too expensive 
it would be cheaper than building another airport he said 
but even less expensive would be highspeed trains which 
travel at speeds up to 200 mph 
johnson said at speeds of 300 mph and distances up to 600 miles 
maglevs could compete economically with aircraft 
he said a maglev system linking chicagos ohare international 
airport with cities such as detroit st louis indianapolis 
milwaukee and minneapolis could significantly reduce congestion at 
the worlds busiest airport 
if you want to expand longerrange domestic and international 
service at ohare maglev certainly is a way of doing it he said 
this week 
johnson said more than half the flights arriving or departing 
daily at ohare or about 1100 of a total of 2000 flights 
cover distances of less than 500 miles 
the argonne report estimates that delays and overcrowding at 
airports cost airlines 5 billion a year and that it would cost 2 
billion to 3 billion to build each of the 15 to 20 us airports 
that experts say are needed to expand the airtransport system into 
the next century 
the maglev system could be built at a cost of 15 million a 
mile and the cost of the individual vehicles is estimated at 25 
million to 5 million each johnson said 
maglevs could be operated on elevated structures built along 
existing interstate highways to link airports to cities in the 
region johnson said for example connecting burlington vt to 
new york city or phoenix to los angeles 
but kumar said trains that dont use magnetic levitation such as 
frances tgv or germanys ice offer advantages of cost 
compatibility with existing track and the capability of hauling 
freight 
highspeed trains are a proven technology maglevs are not 
he said adding that a short line should be constructed to probe 
maglevs feasibility 
a japanese firm has proposed constructing a 20mile maglev line 
between the airport at orlando fla and disney world the idea is 
being considered by florida officials 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

