<TEXT>
lavonne raney took a chance in a fledgling electronics firm 
shed read about and bought a few shares at 15 each 
the time was the early 60s the company was teledyne inc since 
then its stock has shattered the stratosphere trading lately at 
around 350 a share even after several splits 
that was my biggest winner it took three of us around the 
world twice recalled mrs raney of columbus ohio an amateur 
stock dabbler who has long since cashed her teledyne treasure 
there may not be any teledynes left in the twilight of the 20th 
century but that hasnt stopped investors from pouring billions of 
dollars into what they see as potential gold mines startup 
businesses with products and services ranging from robot cashiers 
to toxicwaste neutralizers 
a california company for example is working on a system that 
would prevent waste through recycling another is trying to perfect 
chemicalfree purified water from industrial sewage 
others see riches in warehouselike stores of the future that 
eliminate the middleman or take customer orders via sophisticated 
computers 
hitting it right usually requires a combination of foresight 
and luck said dennis sughrue a researcher at needham 
massbased venture economics inc which tracks trends in 
speculative investments 
the foresightluck mix was electronics in the 60s and computers 
in the 70s people who foresaw that a company hatched in someones 
garage would grow into todays apple computer inc for example 
would have multiplied their investment many times over 
but investing in highrisk businesses is not for the timid like 
the professional poker plays say dont bet what you cant afford 
to lose 
for every apple there are probably 30 to 40 other 
companies you could lose money on said barry r feirstein 
managing director of equitable capital management corp its very 
difficult for an individual investor to get in the ground floor 
of something unless its an industry he knows 
even mrs raney who profited enormously by beating the crowd on 
teledyne admits she stumbled into it and prefers to invest in more 
proven companies 
professional venture capitalists arent flocking to any 
particular industry a report by venture economics shows that all 
the nearly 4 billion put in young companies in 1987 the latest 
year for which complete data was available was spread out with 
no industry getting more than 15 percent 
experts envision growth in specific sectors in communications 
consumer products and services computer hardware and software and 
medicine the venture economics data shows other areas receiving 
adventurousinvestor interest include electronics industrial 
products biotechnology and energy 
within each industry theres a narrowly focused niche and if 
you hit it right you can make it big said sughrue 
finding that niche is the hard part we look at probably 500 
to 800 business plans a year from people coming to us with ideas 
said john b mumford managing general partner at crosspoint 
venture partners of los altos calif 
