<TEXT>
legislation giving the secretary of 
transportation the power to block buyouts of airlines if a 
transaction would imperil flying safety was introduced thursday by 
rep bob carr of michigan 
carrs bill would bar any acquisition that would give the 
airline an even ratio of debt to equity unless the transportation 
department after a full review found the airline could function 
properly after the takeover and that the transaction wouldnt harm 
the public interest 
the east lansing mich democrat said his bill was prompted by 
the recent offer for northwest airlines by billionaire oilman 
marvin davis 
this is not an effort to shield inept management from market 
forces carr said the legislation was intended rather to shield 
the public from highstakes billionaires who would play 
monopoly with the nations air transportation system he said 
the transportation department in ruling whether a takeover 
could proceed would under carrs bill be required to consider the 
financial fitness of the new owner the likelihood that the 
purchaser would comply with federal aviation laws and the 
managerial competence of the purchaser 
if passed the legislation would be retroactive to the beginning 
of this year carr said he knew of no transactions so far concluded 
that would be affected by the bill 
the us airline industry has been largely free from federal 
regulation since 1978 although a takeover must comply with federal 
antitrust laws 
carr argued that safety considerations mean corporate takeovers 
of airlines deserve special treatment 
davis has offered 27 billion or 90 a share to buy 
northwests parent nwa inc northwest based in eagan minn is 
the nations fourthlargest airline 
corporate takeovers are often financed by the issuance of 
highyield junk bonds paid off through the sale of corporate 
assets or stringent costcutting carr argued that reduced 
maintenance was one area where a debtridden airline could cut 
expenditures thereby imperiling the safety of the flying public 
</TEXT>
