<TEXT>
a genericdrug company executive thursday 
accused the food and drug administration of holding up approvals of 
its products to retaliate against the firm for having sparked an 
investigation into alleged bribery at the agency 
roy mcknight chairman of mylan laboratories in pittsburgh told 
a house subcommittee the company has met all the regulatory 
requirements for approval to make a number of drugs at its new 
puerto rico plant drugs for which mylan has approval to make at 
other plants 
we believe that the generic drug division is holding up 
approvals because they believe mylan started this investigation and 
that this was one way to retaliate mcknight told the panel 
rep john dingell dmich chairman of the house energy and 
commerce investigations subcommittee said he will inform fda 
commissioner frank young personally that any retaliation by any 
fda employee against the firms or individuals who testify before us 
will not be tolerated 
dingell also said he will ask young to explain the steps he will 
take to assure that mylan and other companies testifying before the 
subcommittee will not be discriminated against by the fda 
in response to dingells comments acting fda deputy 
commissioner jim benson sent a letter to the congressman assuring 
him there would be no retribution toward any of the companies that 
testify fda spokesman jeff nesbit said in addition a memo was 
sent to the generic drug division warning against any retaliation 
he said 
mylans complaints about arbitrary and discriminatory treatment 
by the fdas generic drug division sparked the investigation that 
so far has resulted in criminal charges against two fda employees 
and a drug company executive 
mcknight chairman and chief executive officer of mylan said 
his company began having trouble with the generic drug division in 
1985 
he said the fda with no uniform standards for drug approvals 
applied the few policies governing the process inconsistently 
also chemist reviewers slowed down the process by making 
unreasonable and repetitive requests for information and mylans 
applications were inexplicably transferred from one chemist to 
another during the process he said 
cheryl blume mylan vice president for scientific affairs said 
the company also has trouble getting information from the agency 
often its walking through the halls of fda and if you see a 
reviewer hell share his information with you she testified 
mcknight and edwin cohen president of barr laboratories one of 
the nations largest generic drug makers recounted a number of 
instances in which they claimed their approval requests were 
mishandled by the agency both alleged that the generic drug 
division favored some companies over others 
mcknight said he brought his complaints to supervisors in the 
division but when they did nothing his company launched its own 
investigation hiring its own investigators 
mylan turned its information over to the house investigations 
subcommittee which began an inquiry a year ago the subcommittee 
later turned over its evidence to the us attorney in baltimore 
for criminal prosecution in april charges were filed against two 
people in the case and earlier this week charles y chang a former 
generic drug division supervisor was charged with taking bribes 
the house panel is continuing its investigation as is the us 
attorney 
fda spokesman nesbit noted that the fda asked the health and 
human services departments inspector general two weeks ago to 
audit the management and practices of the division 
mcknight said little at the agency has changed 
he said mylan has been trying for more than 18 months to get fda 
approval to make several drug products at its new plant in puerto 
rico the company already has approval to make the drugs at its 
morgantown wva plant he said 
he said the company was told by an fda employee that we would 
never get approvals for puerto rico he said the employee was 
walter kletch who appeared before the subcommittee under subpoena 
last week but exercised his fifth amendment right and declined to 
answer any questions 
its business as usual mcknight told the panel 
