<DOCNO> AP890511-0287 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commission in a 
rare action censured the chicago board options exchange on 
thursday accusing the board of failing to enforce its own rules on 
trading manipulation 
the cboe the largest options exchange in the world accepted 
the censure without admitting or denying the governments 
allegations it is only the third time in 10 years that the federal 
commission has censured one of the exchanges it regulates 
the commission said that in 1986 the exchanges business conduct 
committee ignored compelling circumstantial evidence in failing to 
initiate disciplinary action against 12 market makers including a 
former cboe vice chairman and seven affiliated firms 
the agency and the exchange refused to identify the individuals 
or their firms however an exchange source who spoke only on 
condition of anonymity identified one of the 12 as gary lahey who 
was cboe vice chairman at the time of the alleged misconduct in 
1985 
the 12 individuals and their firms were accused of a practice 
known as chumming that is they arranged to trade options 
among themselves primarily for the purpose of creating an 
artificial appearance of activity 
as part of the settlement with the exchange the sec agreed not 
to pursue action against the individuals and firms involved 
according to mary h weiss an attorney in the secs chicago office 
the government is also requiring the exchange to increase its 
surveillance of trading and to periodically inform its members 
about its rules prohibiting trading done to artificially influence 
price or volume 
the options involved included a number of overthecounter 
stocks and options on the standard and poors 250 which tracks 250 
overthecounter industrial stocks the options were listed on 
several exchanges so falsely pumping up activity on the chicago 
exchange could attract more business to it and away from the others 
warren moulds a spokesman for the exchange declined to answer 
questions but he read a statement which said in part in the 
interest of closing out an old matter the cboe voluntarily agreed 
to the entry of the sec order the exchange had already 
completed all undertakings called for in the order prior to the 
order being entered 
</TEXT>
