the us dollar hit an eightmonth high against the 
japanese yen friday morning while share prices on the tokyo stock 
exchange were sharply lower 
the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues a 8914point 
gainer thursday ended the morning session at 3383936 points 
down 24213 points or 07 percent 
after opening at 13540 yen up 085 yen from thursdays close 
of 13455 yen the dollar moved in a range of 1354065 yen the 
currency was being traded at 13548 yen at midday 
it was the first time that the dollar traded at the 13565 level 
since sept 6 
traders said the dollars surge followed overnight gains against 
most major currencies including the japanese yen on overseas 
markets 
the dollars rise was triggered by a decision thursday by us 
president george bush to send more us troops to panama to help 
protect the 51000 american civilians living in that country said 
a trader at the bank of tokyo who spoke anonymously there are 
10000 troops already based at us installations along the panama 
canal 
the us currency is regarded as a safe haven in times of 
international tension 
in a press confernce friday morning finance minister tatsuo 
maruyama said he was not alarmed by the dollars surge the 
dollar was bought due partly to its potential strength at the 
time of an emergency such as confusion over the panamanian 
presidential election maruyama said 
on the tokyo stock exchange share prices declined on a broad 
front due to concerns over the yens fall and the possibility of a 
discount rate hike 
some japanese economists have said the nations monetary 
authorities are waiting to assess price data due later this month 
before deciding on the timing for cutting the discount rate which 
now stands at a postworld war ii low of 25 percent 
